Bastion Host in AWS is a special-purpose EC2 instance that acts as a secure entry point into your private network (VPC). It’s sometimes called a jump server because you “jump” through it to access other instances that don’t have public internet access.

🔑 Key Features
Publicly Accessible → Has a public IP and is placed in a public subnet.

Secure Access → Used to SSH/RDP into instances in private subnets.

Controlled Entry → Acts as the only gateway for administrators to reach private resources.

Hardened Security → Minimal software installed, strict firewall rules, monitored closely.

⚙️ How It Works
You deploy a Bastion Host in a public subnet of your VPC.

You allow inbound SSH (port 22) or RDP (port 3389) only from trusted IPs (like your office).

Once connected to the Bastion Host, you can then SSH/RDP into private EC2 instances inside the VPC.

Private instances don’t need public IPs — they remain isolated and secure.

📊 Bastion Host vs VPN
Feature	           Bastion Host                                     VPN
Purpose	          Secure admin access to private EC2	Secure network-level connectivity
Scope	           Instance-level access	              Entire network access
Setup	         EC2 instance in public subnet	               VGW/TGW + CGW + tunnels
Best Use Case	 Occasional admin access	               Hybrid cloud or remote workforce


🚫 Limitations
Single point of entry → must be hardened and monitored.

Manual access → not ideal for large-scale user connectivity.

Requires careful IAM + Security Group configuration.

✅ Bottom Line: A Bastion Host is your secure “jump box” into AWS private subnets. It’s perfect for administrative access when you don’t want to expose private instances directly to the internet.